body: |
  <p>Freelancing means your gross income hits your account before any taxes are deducted. There's no employer withholding Social Security, Medicare, or federal income tax — that responsibility is entirely yours. For many new freelancers, this isn't obvious until the first annual filing, when the combined federal tax bill lands as a single unexpected number. The quarterly estimated tax system exists to prevent this: it spreads the obligation across the year in four payments, matching the timing of how income arrives.</p>

  <p>The problem is that understanding <em>that</em> quarterly payments exist is different from knowing <em>how much</em> to set aside and <em>when</em>. This checklist covers both — what to track, how to calculate your reserve, and the one habit that makes the whole system manageable without ongoing stress.</p>

  <h2>The Core Problem: Irregular Income, Regular Tax Obligations</h2>

  <p>Tax obligations don't pause during a slow quarter. If your income drops in Q3, your estimated payment is still due on schedule. Missing or underpaying can result in a penalty when you file your return, even if you make up the amount at year end. The amount of each payment is typically based on estimated annual income — which is difficult to predict when your revenue varies month to month.</p>

  <p>The practical fix is a percentage-based reserve system, not a fixed monthly amount. Because freelance income is variable, a fixed figure will be too small in strong months and potentially unnecessary in slow ones. Setting aside a percentage of every payment received — immediately, as it arrives — scales automatically with your actual income and requires no quarterly recalculation.</p>

  <h2>Your Quarterly Tax Checklist</h2>

  <h3>1. Calculate Your Net Income for the Quarter</h3>

  <p>Start with total client payments actually received during the quarter — cash basis, not accrual. An invoice sent in March that gets paid in April counts as April income. Subtract legitimate business expenses: software subscriptions, home office costs, professional development, equipment, and other costs directly tied to your freelance work. The result is your net self-employment income for the quarter — the number used for your reserve calculation.</p>

  <h3>2. Apply Your Set-Aside Percentage</h3>

  <p>A common starting point for US-based freelancers is 25–30% of net income, which covers self-employment tax and federal income tax at moderate income levels. Higher earners typically need 30–35%. Your actual rate depends on total annual income, filing status, available deductions, and state taxes. Because freelance income often varies, treating this as an estimate rather than a fixed rule is important. <a href="/gig-tax-optimizer.html">Use the Gig Tax Optimizer to estimate your specific rate</a> based on your current income and filing status — it's more accurate than any rule of thumb.</p>

  <h3>3. Track Deductible Expenses Throughout the Quarter</h3>

  <p>Deductions reduce taxable income, which lowers both income tax and self-employment tax. Common categories freelancers miss: home office costs (a dedicated workspace proportional to home square footage), software and subscriptions used for work, professional development including courses and books, health insurance premiums when paid personally, and retirement contributions to a Solo 401(k) or SEP IRA. Keep digital receipts throughout the quarter — at year end, the documentation is already complete.</p>

  <h3>4. Set the Money Aside Immediately</h3>

  <p>A separate bank account used only for tax reserves is the most reliable system. When a client payment lands, transfer the set-aside percentage the same day — not at the end of the quarter, not when the payment deadline approaches. This prevents the reserve from being spent accidentally and removes the need to calculate what you owe when time pressure is highest. The money is already there.</p>

  <h3>5. Make Your Estimated Payment Before the Deadline</h3>

  <p>Estimated tax payments are typically due four times a year. Exact dates shift slightly by year and vary by country — check the IRS website or your local tax authority for the current schedule rather than relying on a date from a prior year. In the US, pay through IRS Direct Pay or the EFTPS portal and save the payment confirmation. If you make an error, confirmation records make it easier to identify and correct.</p>

  <h3>6. Reconcile at Year End</h3>

  <p>Quarterly payments are estimates. Your actual tax liability is calculated when you file your annual return. If payments exceeded your actual liability, the difference becomes a refund or a credit toward next year. If you underpaid, you owe the balance — and possibly a small penalty. Good quarterly habits narrow this gap. Reviewing your actual annual income against total quarterly payments each December gives you time to make a catch-up payment before year end if the estimate is running short.</p>

  <h2>What to Do When Income Varies Month to Month</h2>

  <p>Variable income creates a practical problem: the quarterly deadline may arrive during a slow month, when reserves from a stronger month were already spent. This is why the immediate-transfer habit matters so much — it captures the reserve in real time, regardless of what the next month looks like. The reserve builds during strong months and sits available during slow ones.</p>

  <p>For US freelancers with significantly uneven income, the annualized income installment method (IRS Form 2210-AI) allows each quarterly payment to be based on actual income for that specific period rather than a projected annual figure. This can reduce or eliminate underpayment penalties in cases where income swings substantially between quarters. It adds complexity to the calculation, but it's worth understanding if your earnings vary widely from quarter to quarter.</p>

  <h2>The One Habit That Makes This Easy</h2>

  <p>Separate account, immediate transfer, percentage not a fixed amount. This single system removes almost all the operational friction of managing freelance taxes. You stop thinking about taxes as a lump sum to locate at quarter end and start treating them as a line item that funds itself from every payment received. If you're also modeling how your tax reserve affects your overall financial position, the <a href="/break-even-savings-calculator.html">Break-Even Savings Calculator</a> can factor tax costs into your monthly break-even calculation.</p>

  <h2>Use the Calculator to Find Your Rate</h2>

  <p>The <a href="/gig-tax-optimizer.html">Gig Tax Optimizer</a> estimates your quarterly reserve rate based on your net self-employment income and filing status. Run it with this quarter's numbers before your next payment is due — it calculates both the self-employment tax component and the income tax estimate so you can set aside accurately rather than guessing.</p>

  <p><em>This is an educational guide, not personalized financial, tax, or legal advice.</em></p>
